Analyzing Syrian Civil War Casualties¶

by Tyler Basa

Introduction¶

I want to analyze recorded Syrian Civil War Deaths and check certain relationships between categories. For example, I wanted to check the relationship between deaths of certain factions and civilains, combined with the locations or time of their deaths.

Source: https://data.world/polymathic/casualties-of-the-syrian-civil-war

Below are the imports required to use in this tutoral. Pandas is used to create datasets. matplotlib is used to create plots. Datetime is used to properly configure dates to datetime values. Seaborn will be used to plot residuals from using a machine learning model. That model will be used formed by sklearn.linear_model and statsmodels.formula.api

In [164]:
import pandas as pd 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import datetime as dt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols

Notes on the different categories¶

The category values are straight forward for the most part, but Actor categories interestingly have nan values. Whether the reason, lets assume this means the perpetrators were unidentified, but there is already a category for that called "Not identified". Despite looking like it's in datetime format, the date of deaths column is not actually in the type and all columns are "object" dtypes. Lets fill in the nan values in the "actor" column to "not identified", convert the "deathdate" column to datetime, and convert the other columns to string.

In [34]:
data['actor'] = data['actor'].fillna('Not identified') # Fill in all nan values in actor with "not identified"

# Convert all the other columns to string types
data['deathdate']= pd.to_datetime(data['deathdate'])
data['name'] = data['name'].astype('str') 
data['status'] = data['status'].astype('str')
data['gender'] = data['gender'].astype('str') 
data['province'] = data['province'].astype('str') 
data['birthplace'] = data['birthplace'].astype('str') 
data['deathcause'] = data['deathcause'].astype('str') 
data['actor'] = data['actor'].astype('str') 

data.tail()

Gender and Status Analysis¶

Let's get some basic data. First let's compile the amount of casualties and differentiate them by gender first.

In [145]:
data_genderStat = data.groupby(['gender']).name.agg('count').to_frame('count').reset_index()
data_genderStat
Out[145]:
gender count
0 Adult - Female 13695
1 Adult - Male 132889

Let's turn that into a pie chart

In [99]:
plt.figure(figsize=(5,5)) 
plt.title('Deaths in the Syrian Civil War (2011-2019) by gender', fontsize=15)
plt.pie(data_genderStat['count'],labels=data_genderStat['gender'],autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.show()

We can see here that most casualties in the Syrian Civil War are Adult males, with Male children taking second place, with females taking second place. We can assume that the reason for these proportions are because most combatants in the war are Adult males. To test that theory out lets make a plot that compares between gender and status with two pie charts. One shows the proportion of gender between civilians, and another between non-civilians.

In [141]:

We can see that most of the deaths have affected males. In fact, almost 100% of all non-civilian deaths have been Adult males. We could stop right here and say it proves our hypothesis. However, let's take a closer look and make another pie chart, but this time comparing all 8 different permutations. In our "StatusGender" dataset, let's create a new column that combines the strings of both "status" and "gender", then create a new pie chart.

In [190]:
StatusGender['StatusGender'] = StatusGender["status"] + " + " + StatusGender["gender"]
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10)) 
plt.title('All Deaths in the Syrian Civil War (2011-2019) by gender and status', fontsize=15)
plt.pie(StatusGender['count'],labels=StatusGender['StatusGender'],autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.show()

Now when compiling all casualties in the dataset, we see that Civilian Adult Males take up half of them. In fact, there are actually more Civilian casualties than Non-civilian casualties overall. This essentially disproves my initial hypothesis that the reason for most Adult males dying is solely because of non-civilians.

Very interestingly most of the identified casualties for both Civilians and Non-Civilians were indeed caused by Syrian Government forces. There are some more intersting proportional differences, such as where International Coalition Forces killed 8.3% of the civilians in the dataset, but only 1.6% of non-civilians. ISIS also shares almost 15% of civilian deaths, but share almost 27% of non-civilian casualties. Overall though, the pie chart indicates that the majority of deaths, where the actor is identified, is the fault of the Syrian Government. While we unfortunately cannot identify the perpetrator in all casualties, this does unofficially imply that most of those unidentified deaths may also have been the result of Syrian Government actions. This is especially in the case of the Ghouta Chemical attack where the only identified perpetrators were Syrian Government Forces.

Machine Learning¶

Let's test out a linear regression model, aka ordinary least squares. Unfortunately, using the statsmodel linear regression model is unable to utilize datetime, so we will have to conver the datetime numerically for now. Let's get the raw statistics of using linear regression machine learning between number of deaths and the date, before we start plotting.

In [170]:
data_timeplot_regress = data_timeplot
data_timeplot_regress["deathdate"] = data_timeplot_regress['deathdate'].map(dt.datetime.toordinal) # convert 
est = ols(formula = 'deathdate ~ count', data = data_timeplot_regress).fit()
print(est.summary())

One thing we can note is that the P-values are zero, indicating that there is a relationship between the date and casualty count on a certain day. Now let's plot the linear regession line into the date-count lineplot.

In [184]:
X = data_timeplot_regress['deathdate'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
Y = data_timeplot_regress['count'].values.reshape(-1, 1)
linear_regressor = LinearRegression()
linear_regressor.fit(X, Y)
Y_pred = linear_regressor.predict(X)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10)) 

plt.plot(X, Y)
plt.plot(X, Y_pred, color='red') # plots regression line
plt.show()

The linear regression line shows that Syrian Civil war casualties have indeed been steadly decreasing since. However is this model very strong? Let's use seaborn to plot the residuals from using the predictor, and get a score on how accurate the linear regressor is.

In [193]:
y_hat = linear_regressor.predict(X)
sns.distplot(Y - y_hat)
plt.title("Residuals per casualty count", size=18)
linear_regressor.score(X,Y)

Most of the residuals are between 0-200 as that is the total number of casualties in most days. It also has a low score of 0.128. Other machine learning models may be more accurate than using the linear regression model.

Conclusion¶

To recap, we analyzed Syrian Civil War deaths and made a few hypothesis' that were essentially disproven. We saw that Adult Males made up a great majority of the casualties in the war. I hypothesized it was because most non-civilian deaths were Adult Males, which was true, but the vast majority of Adult Male casualties were actually civilians. We analyzed the casualties in the date of the Ghouta Chemical Attack, which informally implied why the Syrian Government was blamed for it. I hypothesized the reason for most casualties having an unidentified perpetrator was because most casualties were civilians, but the distributions of actors between civilians and non-civilians were the same.

Using the Linear Regression model for machine learning, we found that the casualty count has been decreasing on average between 2011-2019. However, we also learned that the linear regressor model was not very accurate and strong for the most part.
